{
  "answer": "Both works are in the corpus. Here are their foundational statements on land ownership and the metaphysical assumptions each makes about the person-soil relationship.\n\n**Comte, Traité de la propriété Vol I (charles-comte-traite-de-la-propriete-vol-i-2c7a99)**\n\nFoundational statements (primarily Chapters 4, 5, and 9):\n- Chapter 5 (p-e68210): 'The action of an organized being that unites to its own substance the things by means of which it grows, strengthens, and reproduces, is what we name appropriation.' Appropriation is a biological, natural act common to all living beings.\n- Chapter 4 (p-7e2792): 'the appropriation, by nations, families, and individuals, of the various things on which human industry can be exercised, is a necessity of our nature' — property is not a legal convention but a law of nature.\n- Chapter 9 (p-302405): 'In all positions, it is therefore by his labor that man appropriates the things he needs to exist.' And: 'the greatest part of the value that lands have among civilized nations is the result of the action that men have exercised upon them' — raw soil contributes only 1/1200th of the value cultivated land holds in France; the rest is the product of human industry.\n- Chapter 9 (p-7b9327): 'the men who, first, put the land into cultivation... and who thus appropriated it to themselves, have snatched nothing from their fellow men.'\n\nMetaphysical assumption: The person is an active, productive agent who creates virtually all the value in land through labor. The soil in its natural state has negligible worth; its value is almost entirely anthropogenic. The person-soil relationship is therefore **productive and transformative** — labor is what forges the moral bond between person and land. Ownership is grounded in this creative act, not in divine grant or political command. The soil is passive matter; the person activates it.\n\n**Viṣṇu Smṛti (unknown-visnu-smrti-27f0d8)**\n\nFoundational statements (primarily Chapters 1, 3, and 17):\n- Chapter 1 (Vi_1.1–1.13): The earth (Vasudhā/Dhara) is a divine goddess, lifted from the cosmic ocean by Vishnu in Boar form and 'placed in a firm, fixed position' for the welfare of the worlds. The earth has subjectivity and asks Vishnu for support.\n- Chapter 1 (Vi_1.47): Vishnu tells the Earth: 'Good people who delight in the practices of the varṇas and āśramas, devoted solely to the scriptures, They, O Dhara, will support you; the burden of you is placed upon them.' The earth is sustained by dharma-following humans — the relationship is cosmic duty, not productive transformation.\n- Chapter 3 (Vi_3.22, 3.28): 'For tax, he shall take a sixth part of the grain annually from his subjects' and 'the king receives a sixth part of the good and evil deeds of his subjects.' The king's entitlement to land's produce is tied to his cosmic role as protector — his governance IS the mechanism by which the earth's bounty flows.\n- Chapter 3 (Vi_3.81–3.83): 'he should grant land to Brāhmaṇas' with documented titles; 'he shall not confiscate land granted by another.' Private land-holding is mediated by royal sanction; the king is the source of legitimate land tenure.\n- Chapter 17 (Vi_17.13): 'In his absence [no heirs], it goes to the king, except for the property of a Brāhmaṇa.' The king is the residual owner of all non-Brahminical property.\n\nMetaphysical assumption: The earth is a sacred divine entity under cosmic governance, not passive matter awaiting transformation. The person-soil relationship is **custodial and hierarchically ordered** — humans hold land not because they created value in it but because they occupy a position in the dharmic hierarchy (varna, āśrama) ratified by the king's protection. The king takes a sixth part because his protection is the cosmic condition under which the earth's sustenance flows to anyone. Land grants flow downward from Vishnu → dharmic order → king → subjects. The assumption is that **cosmic order (dharma), not labor**, constitutes the person's claim to soil.\n\n**Contrast**: Comte assumes the person and soil are linked by productive transformation — labor creates value and therefore ownership. The Viṣṇu Smṛti assumes the person and soil are linked by cosmic hierarchy — dharmic duty and royal mediation create the condition under which soil may be held. For Comte, the soil is ontologically inert until the person acts on it; for the Viṣṇu Smṛti, the soil is ontologically divine and the person receives access to it by occupying their proper place in a divinely-ordered social cosmos.",
